2026-04-21 01:26:34 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['Power-control interconnect cabling', 'Control-load interconnect cabling'] hypothesis_explanation='Given the design, when the modules are correctly wired and the supply polarity is correct, the red inverted‑cables indicator in the control module should be OFF in normal operation. It turns ON only when the 12 V and 0 V lines from adjacent modules are swapped (i.e., the control module sees its inputs reversed relative to its internal reference).\n\nObserved symptoms:\n- The green LED on the power module is ON → 12 V source is present and correctly oriented inside the power module.\n- The red LED on the control module is ON → the control module senses reversed polarity between its two external lines.\n- The load (lamp) does not turn on when the switch is operated → either the load is not receiving proper polarity/voltage, or the series path through the switch is not correctly oriented.\n\nThese three symptoms together are most consistently explained by incorrect wiring of the unmarked cables between modules (a configuration fault, not an internal component failure):\n1) At least one pair of cables between the power and control modules is polarity‑reversed. This directly causes the inverted‑cables indicator LED in the control module to light.\n2) Because the control module’s external polarity is wrong, the line feeding the load module is also incorrect, so the diode in the load module is reverse‑biased and blocks current, preventing the lamp from lighting even when the switch is ON.\n3) There is no evidence of failed LEDs, lamps, or diodes; the only symptom pointing to a fault is the red indicator itself, which explicitly signals swapped lines.\n\nTherefore, the most likely root cause is that one or both inter-module cable pairs are connected with reversed polarity (mis‑plugged connectors). The repair action would be to identify and correct the polarity of the cable connections between power–control and control–load modules so that the 12 V and 0 V lines are consistently oriented through all modules.'
